The Nord Stream, new door nTry of Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, directly linking Western Europe with the Russia from the bottom of the Baltic Sea, came into service.
To provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brightness.
More than 500 guests including four heads of State and Government attended, last Tuesday, on the shores of the Baltic, between Orchestra and end buffet, at the opening of Nord Stream, the new pipeline linking directly, under the sea, the Russia to the Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands Mark Rutte together turned the wheel of the valve Commander Russian in the West European network gas entry.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas will reach every year in Western Europe by a first tube of 1,224 km linking the St. Petersburg region in the Land of Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed end of 2012, to issue a total 55 billion cubic metres of gas, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And it already refers to the possibility to build a third on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion time and time of this huge site has tunes of victory.
The project had been strongly challenged by the Poland and the Baltic countries.
Nord Stream will indeed deliver gas directly into Germany, avoiding a land crossing by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At the time, these two countries lose a little of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to influence the Russia by threatening to cut off access to West European markets.
